{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528668"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:46:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:46:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14323"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14323"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.2,0.12,0.07,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7018"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111837"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7018"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93907"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3069"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17384"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46284"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111837"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe, intermittent abdominal pain and intractable vomiting for the past two days. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On further questioning, he reports daily cannabis use for the past five years. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft but diffusely tender without guarding or rebound. Investigations reveal normal full blood count, electrolytes, and liver function tests. The patient has been taking regular hot showers and utilising heat packs, but they have not provided symptom relief.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer intravenous haloperidol","Prescribe oral ondansetron","Apply topical capsaicin cream","Administer intravenous morphine","Administer intravenous metoclopramide"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome (CHS): chronic cannabis use, cyclic vomiting, abdominal pain, and characteristic relief-seeking behavior with hot showers. Since hot showers have failed to provide relief, pharmacological intervention is now indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister intravenous haloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Haloperidol has emerged as a particularly effective treatment for CHS through its D2 receptor antagonism in the central nervous system. Multiple case series and retrospective studies have demonstrated its efficacy in rapidly controlling symptoms when traditional antiemetics have failed. The typical dose is 1-5 mg intravenously with good symptom control often achieved within 1-2 hours. Studies have shown that haloperidol leads to significant improvement in acute nausea and abdominal pain within two hours, reduces emergency department length of stay, decreases time to discharge, and minimises the need for additional rescue medications when compared to standard antiemetics such as ondansetron.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribe oral ondansetron\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be effective in this scenario. Despite being a first-line antiemetic for many conditions, 5-HT3 receptor antagonists like ondansetron typically provide minimal relief in CHS (particularly once the hyperemesis phase has started). The HAVOC trial, a randomised controlled trial comparing intravenous haloperidol to ondansetron for CHS, demonstrated that haloperidol was significantly more effective, with 82% of patients achieving adequate symptom control compared to only 37% in the ondansetron group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApply topical capsaicin cream\u003C/strong\u003E has shown some promise in CHS management through its action on TRPV1 receptors (the same mechanism that explains the relief from hot showers). However, it is generally considered a second-line or adjunctive therapy rather than the most appropriate next step when a patient is actively vomiting in the Emergency Department.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister intravenous morphine\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this context. Opioids can worsen nausea and vomiting in CHS patients and may mask important clinical signs if there is an alternative diagnosis. Additionally, there are concerns about potential substance dependence in a patient already struggling with cannabis use disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister intravenous metoclopramide\u003C/strong\u003E, like ondansetron, typically provides minimal relief in CHS despite its effectiveness for other causes of vomiting. Dopamine antagonists with central effects (like haloperidol) have demonstrated superior efficacy compared to primarily peripheral-acting agents like metoclopramide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeyond acute symptom management, patient education about cannabis cessation is essential, as this remains the only definitive treatment for CHS. Benzodiazepines may also be considered as adjunctive therapy due to their anxiolytic properties and potential antiemetic effects through GABA-mediated pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haloperidol is an effective treatment for acute nausea and vomiting in cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome (CHS) if first line management of hot showers has not helped.","Cessation of cannabis use is the definitive treatment for CHS.","Traditional antiemetics like ondansetron and metoclopramide are often ineffective in cannabinoid hyperemesis syndrome."],"references":["Ruberto AJ, Sivilotti MLA, Forrester S, Hall AK, Crawford FM, Day AG. Intravenous haloperidol versus ondansetron for cannabis hyperemesis syndrome (HaVOC): a randomized, controlled trial. Ann Emerg Med 2021;77(6):613-9. Available at: https://rebelem.com/the-havoc-trial-iv-haloperidol-vs-ondansetron-for-cannabis-hyperemesis-syndrome/","Hebbard G, Metz A. Nausea and vomiting in adults: a diagnostic approach. Australian family physician. 2007 Sep;36(9).","Trajkovski A, Lang E. Haloperidol as an anti-emetic for Cannabis Hyperemesis Syndrome in the ED. CJEM. 2021 May;23(3):312-313. doi: 10.1007/s43678-021-00122-x. Epub 2021 Apr 9. PMID: 33835429.","Angulo MI. Cannabinoid Hyperemesis Syndrome. JAMA. 2024;332(17):1496. doi:10.1001/jama.2024.9716","AGA Clinical Practice Update on Diagnosis and Management of Cannabinoid Hyperemesis Syndrome: Commentary. Rubio-Tapia, Alberto et al. Gastroenterology, Volume 166, Issue 5, 930 - 934.e1","Gajendran M, Sifuentes J, Bashashati M, McCallum R. Cannabinoid Hyperemesis Syndrome: Definition, Pathophysiology, Clinical Spectrum, Insights into Acute and Long-Term Management. Journal of Investigative Medicine. 2020;68(8):1309-1316. doi:10.1136/jim-2020-001564"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93907"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14323"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93907"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T11:13:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-03T10:26:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7018"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111837"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their 